	painsBodyHtml={`<p>People leave faith, or never arrive, for reasons that deserve to be taken seriously — not argued away. Some watched the gap between what religious people preached and how they lived, and couldn't unsee it. Some were genuinely hurt: judged, shamed, controlled, or wounded by the very people who claimed to speak for God. Some were handed a God who was mostly anger and rules — a cosmic scorekeeper waiting to catch them — and walked away from that picture entirely. Others simply find the whole thing implausible, or irrelevant to an honest life. Those are real reasons, and none of them make you broken or rebellious.</p><p>And yet — a lot of people who've left still carry something quiet. A question that doesn't fully close. A wonder, on a clear night or in a hard hour, about whether there's anything underneath it all. If that's you, you don't owe anyone an answer. But it might be worth considering this: maybe what you rejected wasn't the real thing. Maybe the God worth your honest attention is not the one you were warned about — but a Father who was after your heart the whole time, and never once needed you to perform for it.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
