	faqs={[
		{ question: `Is God real?`, answer: `That's one of the most honest questions a person can ask, and you're allowed to ask it without pretending to know the answer. This page won't try to win a debate. What it offers is the chance to read the source for yourself: Acts 17:27 describes a God who is "not far from any one of us" and who honors the seeking. Rather than take anyone's word for it, read and listen free at fathersheartbible.com/read and decide what you actually find there.` },
		{ question: `Why should I read the Bible if I'm not religious?`, answer: `Because the Bible is one of the most influential texts in human history, and most people — religious or not — have only ever heard it secondhand, often the angry, rule-heavy version. Reading it yourself lets you replace the caricature with the actual text. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals God as a Father, not a scorekeeper, wherever Scripture does. You don't have to believe anything to read it free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Can I read the Bible without joining a church?`, answer: `Absolutely. No church, no membership, no account, no one watching. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online, privately, on your own terms — open fathersheartbible.com/read on your phone and read or hear any book whenever you want. If church is part of why you left in the first place, you can explore the text completely on your own.` },
		{ question: `What if I have doubts?`, answer: `Then you're in good company — Scripture is full of people who doubted, questioned, and argued with God honestly. Pew Research finds that questioning religious teachings is one of the top reasons people leave faith, and that doubt isn't treated here as a problem to fix. Psalm 139 describes a God who already knows your thoughts — doubts and all — and doesn't flinch. Bring every question. Read freely at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What if I was hurt by religion or the church?`, answer: `That's real, and it shouldn't be argued away. A lot of people walked away because of genuine harm — judgment, hypocrisy, control, or a God presented as mostly anger. The honest possibility worth considering is that what hurt you was never the real thing. Jesus' picture of God in Luke 15 is a father who runs to the one who left — no lecture, no probation. You can read that for yourself, privately and free, at fathersheartbible.com/read, with no one asking anything of you.` },
		{ question: `What is the Bible really about?`, answer: `Strip away the religion and the rules, and the Father's Heart Bible™ makes the case that it's about a Father after the hearts of His children — not a list of demands or a system to fear. From the father running to meet his lost son in Luke 15 to "the kind of love the Father has given us" in 1 John 3:1, the through-line is love, not condemnation. Read it free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read and see whether that holds up.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different?`, answer: `It's a fresh English translation that reveals God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so instead of meeting the distant, angry rule-keeper many people walked away from, you meet the One the text actually points to. For someone who's skeptical, deconstructing, or done with religion, that reframes the whole thing: you're invited to read as a curious adult, not a convert, and decide for yourself. It's free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
